cs.LO, cs.DS, cs.AI, cs.PL, cs.FL

This paper deals with the complexity of model checking for various objectives in graphs and Markov Decision Processes (MDPs), which are topics typically studied in the areas of logic (cs.LO), data structures (cs.DS), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), programming languages (cs.PL), and formal languages and automata theory (cs.FL). The paper's focus on polynomial-time problems and $\omega$-regular objectives suggests that it is more likely to be classified under cs.LO and cs.DS, but the use of MDPs and the study of disjunctive queries and dual objectives also make cs.AI and cs.PL plausible categories. Finally, the paper's use of conditional lower bounds based on widely believed assumptions about the complexity of CNF-SAT and combinatorial Boolean matrix multiplication suggests that it may also be relevant to the area of computational complexity theory (cs.CC).
